segments.text: I mentioned Gwen Flint.
Gwen was from the previous year, and Gwen went on to law school, has done well, raised a family, good attorney.
Jeff Dunn then followed Steve.
Jeff was Jewish, and Jeff went to law school, has done well, is an attorney up in the Dallas area.
Let's digress a second.
Did you encounter any
incidents, particularly in those years, but in general, that had to do with somebody being Jewish or Catholic or nothing or whatever?
No, and the reason I slid into Jeff is I wanted to capture one more and then relate to the previous four.
And Fred McClure was after Jeff Dunham.
So we went from a Jewish youngster to a black youngster.
And to tie that, Jeff and Steve were roommates in Houston when Steve had the heart attack.
And at the funeral in New Braunfels, after Steve died, Jeff helped the family set up services
So we had a Jewish kid, and Steve was in a church of Christ, and Fred sang Amazing Grace at the funeral in the choir loft.
And so I think it was typical of what A&M was all about.
A mixture of people, conservative values, and good human beings.
Do you agree with me?
I've always generalized that
The major criteria in here is, are you an Aggie or not?
If you are, then whether you're left-handed, tall, short, Jewish, Irish, doesn't, that's coincidental.
One thing about Jeff, at my dinners I used to always say a Catholic blessing, and so Jeff got all over me, the Jewish dude.
I said things that sort of offended the Jewish people.
And I said, Jeff, that's fine.
I said, when you pay for the dinner, then you can start saying the Jewish blessing.
But I did amend the blessing to not offend.
It was something of which I was unaware.
But they were all good kids.
In regard to the core, we had some good kids that...
We had Scott Everhart that first year as Corps Commander along with Randy.
We had one young man who served as Vice President for Student Government and Vice President of the MSC.
He's the only one that's ever done that.
He's an attorney now and I'm trying to grab his name, David.
His dad was an architect from Fort Worth, a very prominent former student.
He died of a heart attack in Cali.
I can't think of his last name.
Was Barbara Sears the first female student body officer?
Yeah.
Barbara and Steve went together for a long time and then
even after they left here, and then Barb went to Duke, and she stayed in touch with us, and her Steve went to Hollywood.
Barb got a doctoral degree, and I'm thinking it's in, I think biochemistry.
She's on the faculty now at Michigan to study, and her specialty was
I was going to say genealogy, but it's not genealogy.
What do they call it?
Do you remember any pluses or minuses of a female running for student body office and winning?
I think the students slid into them very easily.
At A&M it really was.
For example, you were talking about being left-handed or right-handed or black or white or Jewish or whatever.
If you were capable, you were selected or elected.
And if you weren't, you were not.
With one exception, and we talked about that, it's related to Ross, Sol Ross in the Corps.
They weren't.
interested in selecting women initially for that group.
I think had it been allowed to run its course, it would have happened.
And they would have selected or elected women into that organization just like they did in student government and other things.
The one I've told on Barbara Sears is her standing on the steps of the Cushing Library where the

voting booths were on the inside, having worked carefully on her eye makeup that day and her hair in a pretty dress, giving out cards with her name on it, and then saying softly as they accepted the card, would you vote for me?
And she admitted to me, yes, that's what she did do.
Do you remember any particular student leadership campaigns for certain major items, issues, during those early years?
No, I think the things that they argued about are those that they still argue about.
they will say to some degree before they get involved in those offices that the administration doesn't listen to the students and so on.
And once they get involved, they find out that they do and they are heard, they are listened to.
I was reading battalions the other day, it was the same thing as related to some elections.
No, I don't think, no.
Not anything major.
It's always been, well, I do remember one early on that was funny, humorous, but it had to do with the fences around the campus.
I don't know if you remember that.
The students were upset that they were going to put fences around and kind of create a
prison-like environment with the fences.
So there were things like that that came up.
So they were interesting and more fun than they were really serious and a major problem.
Since I'm going to talk to Fred McClure tomorrow, do you recall any specific events, plus or minus, during his year as student body president?
Fred had a good year.
The thing I remember the most was about Fred was in spring convocation when he was late getting back.
He was out on the west coast someplace and had to hustle to get back.
And he talked like a Baptist minister, even as a young student body president.
And his presence at that spring convocation as a young student, I thought was very well with all the higher ups administratively and academically.
And he could hold his own already.
Because if I'm not mistaken, that was centennial year.

and we had all been thinking about that as the kind of culmination of dr williams's and then the heart attack took him away from that um the i was the master of ceremonies i was looking at some stuff the other day that had kind of slipped away then back at the inauguration
Kent Caperton spoke for the students, I spoke for the faculty at the Williams inauguration.
So that, I remember that beginning.
Other, do you remember any other centennial year events and highlights?
I remember Ed Cooper was the one responsible for all of that.
He did a good job of pulling everything together.
other than the fact that everything went smooth and it was a nice time, enjoyable.
I know a lot of work went in by the committee and all those who were involved with it.
I really wasn't, you know, although I was master of ceremonies at that function, it just seemed like everything went smoothly and everything went well.
Alright, let's kind of, let's see, in terms of Fred, I've told this one, you saw it get, after Fred left, and of course all my kids got to know Fred really well.
They had him, we had him back for a commencement speech, and he flew in on a Friday, and I woke up on Saturday morning, getting ready to go to the commencement, and my son
He was up and he came down to the kitchen and we were talking and he said, guess who was at the chicken with us last night?
And I said, who?
He said, Fred.
I said, son of a gun.
He said, well, Fred had come in and they had gotten a bunch of beer and everybody and they drank beer.
And the next morning, we're waiting, Fred had come.
The faculty has to get ready to move out.
Fred's out there.
Fred's out there.
Just before we got ready to move out, do you remember?
Fred?
Oh, you weren't here, probably.
No.
Fred shows up.
And so we, I'm laughing and teasing with him, didn't say anything about Jay at all.
We went up on the stage all week.
Fred made a speech.
And boy, he did a good job.
But he was just sweating.
I mean, he was just pouring.
And he came back, and he sat down.
And I leaned over and I said, hey, everybody's thinking it's all that heat with those lights blaring on you.
I know it's all that damn beer you drank last night.
But Fred was good as gold.
Fred had a good year.
Those kids early on had good years.
Steve had a good year.
Jeff had a good year.
Fred had a good year.
Go ahead.
I was going to say, let's kind of draw this to a conclusion.
Do you remember any good funnies, any good laughs during those early years?
Well, I mentioned about Dr. Williams hitting a golf ball, kicking me in the shin.
Let's see, now wait.
The golf ball.
He told me one time, I asked him why did he play golf soon after the board would leave town.
And he told me that because he could imagine that there were certain board members rumped on the golf ball.
In fact, he would normally call that afternoon.
That's right.
And my secretary would know that when he called that we rescheduled everything, no matter who it was or whatever.
Because I wanted him to, you know.
When you all were playing golf, did he ever kind of unwind?
He did, but not in regard to conversation.
But that's what I mean.
He didn't talk about things that were bothering him.
I don't know that he did that with anyone unless it was Mrs. Williams.
Yeah.
I, of course, since he didn't do it with me, I assumed that he did it with John, but I never did ask John.
If so, I'm not aware of it.
Me, half.
He just, he was not that tight.
No.
But, you know, just getting out in the fresh air and relaxing was the thing that got him away.
He didn't have to, he didn't have to let go a whole lot.
Alright, do you remember any goofy student pranks?
Stunts.
Goofs.
To him or to me?
No, anything.
I was trying to think of some funnies, help you think of some funnies to conclude this section of the...
Well, on election night the kids would come over to my house and wait for me at 5 30 in the morning as I came walking out.
After counting the ballots, remember we used to have to count the ballots on the computer, and they knew that we'd go to breakfast together and so we used to do that.
A cute thing, after one of the football games, we used to have everyone come by the house, all the friends and former students and so on at the house on campus.
So after a football game, there would be loads and loads of people.
And after this one football game, it was about midnight, and the doorbell rang.
We had lots of people sitting around.
I went to the door.
young lady and young man standing at the door, and so I invited them in, two other students.
They came over and, trying to get them to sit down, they couldn't sit down, they were very antsy, so I sat down.
They got in front of me, and the young lady's father, she was from Fort Worth, had died a couple years before, and I had helped him through that when he had.
And so the young man had asked her to marry him that evening.
They wanted to share that with me, and she wanted to ask me if I would give her away at her wedding.
So that was an interesting thing that happened.
You know, Haskell, I'm sure there were loads and loads of funny things that happened.
They just kind of slip away.
I've got...
a bunch of files and probably the next time before we sit down and talk, I'll just kind of go through and try to brief myself.
Let's see, then I'll close with this one.
I've been interviewing the past presidents of the Former Students Association.
Somebody gave me, planted a question with me that I've asked them.
I've asked them,
Well, did they know anything about any secret fraternities while they were students?
Almost all of them have said no.
Are you at liberty to say anything about secret fraternities at A&M?
I know they've existed.
I know for a fact they've existed.
Have they existed in your days at A&M?
No.
OK. And I would assume that they still exist.
That's what I have surmised.
And as far as I can determine from what I've learned from these few people who will admit they know something, that their primary purpose was to help get their own members in leadership positions.
Well, that may be part of it.
primarily related to the core.
OK, yeah, yeah, yeah.
And to get their people in the key core positions and or the key student body position.
And I've heard references to two, the TTs and what was the other one?
I can't remember.
I can't remember what the other one was.
Oh.

And I want to run this one by Mr. Evans, because I heard that there was one that had a swastika as its logo way back in his day as a student, long before the Nazi party came into being, because that was the Navajo good luck sign.
So let's see.
All right, what day did y'all get to, when you moved here, what day was it when you arrived?
15th of August, 1970.
And what was the climate like that day?
It was a pretty day.
The sun wasn't bothered by the heat, but we were coming from Commerce.
It had been hot all summer there, so I'm assuming that temperature wise it was about the same.
We moved into an apartment over on Harvey Road, a three bedroom apartment.
The kids were real thrilled about us coming in.
We gave the two oldest girls the master bedroom.
And Mary Dallin and I took the smaller bedroom.
And that was to pacify those two older girls.
Because they were very unhappy with their daddy about taking this child.
They were 13 and 11.
And they were already missing their friends.
And of course, those two died in the real Aggies.
Everything was changed.
I was able to use that years later, my daddy making the decision sometimes when it doesn't seem like it's very good and sometimes it's in their own best interest.
But yeah, and I'm, what's his name, home, Adam's, the one that moved us.

No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no,
Who was that?
Connolly.
Yeah.
Connolly brothers.
Connolly moving and storage.
Yeah, moving and storage.
They moved us.
Homer moved us on campus when we moved from the apartment.
Well, I think he moved us from the apartment to the house on Guadalupe and then from Guadalupe out to the campus.
You remember Homer, right?
Oh, yes, yes.
So you think that...
That two minutes or so you spent with Dr. Williams early on, on that first interview visit, may have had a fairly important effect on your life.
Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes.
Yes, it did.
I wasn't sure at the time what effect it had.
Yes, it did.
It was just an interesting period in regard to thinking that you're not being considered and you're just wasting his time when it really was not the way it was.
Right, and now this will be the last question.
What message would you like me to pass on to Margaret Williams?
Oh, give her my love.
Tell her I think of her often and very positively.
It was good to see that the girls, and especially Mary,
dedication.
I got to know Mary real well.
I didn't know her other daughter.
And I was sorry that she wasn't, that Martin wasn't, to see her.
They were very good to me, to us.
And we missed them.
We were sorry things went the way they went.
And then our relationship didn't last for that long.
